abstract: The artist Maurizio Cattelan’s taped banana at Art Basel Miami prompted so much buzz and commotion that it was removed on Sunday before the end of the fair.
snippet: The artist Maurizio Cattelan’s taped banana at Art Basel Miami prompted so much buzz and commotion that it was removed on Sunday before the end of the fair.
lead_paragraph: The banana that consumed the art world has taken early retirement.

abstract: The International Monetary Fund, in conditionally agreeing to lend the country $5.5 billion over three years, cited “impressive progress” under President Volodymyr Zelensky.
snippet: The International Monetary Fund, in conditionally agreeing to lend the country $5.5 billion over three years, cited “impressive progress” under President Volodymyr Zelensky.
lead_paragraph: KYIV, Ukraine — The International Monetary Fund has agreed to lend $5.5 billion to Ukraine, a move viewed as a stamp of approval for President Volodymyr Zelensky’s anticorruption and economic policies.

abstract: It’s that stressful time in the holiday shopping season when we’re all playing chicken with sales — wait a little longer, and the price could go down; wait too long, and things will sell out. Some gift options that probably won’t get cheaper? French wine, cheese, perfume and handbags, which are the latest victims of President Trump’s tariff wars. Here’s what to know about that, plus other top stories in the business and tech worlds.

abstract: An opening sketch featured celebrities playing the world leaders who were caught on tape gossiping about President Trump.
snippet: An opening sketch featured celebrities playing the world leaders who were caught on tape gossiping about President Trump.
lead_paragraph: If there are two things that “Saturday Night Live” loves, it’s geopolitics and celebrity cameos, and it got to indulge both of these infatuations in this weekend’s opening sketch, set within the socially ruthless confines of the NATO cafeteria.

abstract: Throngs of people poured into major thoroughfares for a march marking Human Rights Day.
snippet: Throngs of people poured into major thoroughfares for a march marking Human Rights Day.
lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — Hundreds of thousands of protesters, basking in a recent election victory by Hong Kong’s pro-democracy camp, poured onto the city’s streets on Sunday in one of the largest marches in weeks to pressure the government to meet demands for greater civil liberties.

abstract: The North said it conducted an “important test” at a missile-engine site ahead of a Dec. 31 deadline set by its leader, Kim Jong-un, for a new proposal from Washington on denuclearization.
snippet: The North said it conducted an “important test” at a missile-engine site ahead of a Dec. 31 deadline set by its leader, Kim Jong-un, for a new proposal from Washington on denuclearization.
lead_paragraph: SEOUL, South Korea — With North Korea’s deadline for American concessions fast approaching, the North announced Sunday that it had conducted a “very important test” at a missile-engine site, rapidly ramping up pressure after months of carefully calibrated provocations.

headline_main: North Korea Turns Up Pressure on the United States for Concessions
headline_print_headline: North Korea Says That It Conducted ‘Very Important Test’ at a Missile-Engine Site
byline_original: By Choe Sang-Hun and David E. Sanger

abstract: Before issuing his own condolences, the president channeled the Saudi king’s, and avoided any discussion of the hard questions about why the U.S. is training Saudi officers.
snippet: Before issuing his own condolences, the president channeled the Saudi king’s, and avoided any discussion of the hard questions about why the U.S. is training Saudi officers.
lead_paragraph: FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. — When a Saudi Air Force officer opened fire on his classmates at a naval base in Pensacola, Fla., on Friday, he killed three, wounded eight and exposed anew the strange dynamic between President Trump and the Saudi leadership: The president’s first instinct was to tamp down any suggestion that the Saudi government needed to be held to account.

abstract: Investigators are still trying to understand the motive of a Saudi trainee who fatally shot three people at Naval Air Station Pensacola.
snippet: Investigators are still trying to understand the motive of a Saudi trainee who fatally shot three people at Naval Air Station Pensacola.
lead_paragraph: PENSACOLA, Fla. — As federal authorities worked on Saturday to piece together clues to last week’s attack at a Florida military training base, new details emerged about the gunman, a Saudi trainee who had apparently shown videos of mass shootings at a dinner party the night before.
